ACTOR2: Civilians (United States)
NOTES: On 25 May 2020, four Minneapolis police officers arrested a Black man, George Floyd, in Minneapolis (Minnesota) for allegedly using a counterfeit 20 dollar bill at a store. One white police officer knelt on Floyd's neck for a total of 8 minutes and 46 seconds, leading to his death. Prior to this, the four officers handcuffed Floyd and held him in a facedown position. Three of the officers applied pressure to his neck, torso, and back. Floyd repeatedly said "I can't breathe" before falling unconscious. Floyd was taken away by EMTs and later pronounced dead. All four officers were fired. The officer who used his knee to pin Floyd down was charged with second-degree murder. The other three officers were charged with aiding and abetting the murder. This event has galvanized support for the Black Lives Matter movement and triggered demonstrations worldwide.

ASSOC_ACTOR_1: BLM: Black Lives Matter; Civilians (United States); Journalists (United States)
ACTOR2: Police Forces of the United States (2017-)
SOURCE: Los Angeles Times; AP; US Press Freedom Tracker; NBC4 Southern California; KTLA5; Committee to Protect Journalists; Physicians for Human Rights; Q13 Fox
NOTES: On 30 May 2020, at least 400 people marched from Pan Pacific Park in Los Angeles (California) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. The demonstration turned violent when some demonstrators began looting. Police intervened and used "kettling" tactics to fragment demonstrators into smaller groups. Other officers stood atop the Etz Jacob Synagogue and fired projectiles down on demonstrators below. At least 12 people were hit in the head by kinetic impact projectiles launched by police officers. One person sustained a traumatic brain injury. The extent of others' injuries were unclear. There is no evidence that these 12 people were behaving according to the LAPD guidelines that would warrant "the use of lethal force." Eleven journalists were targeted by police with rubber bullets, control ammunitions, and tear gas. One was hit in the stomach after declaring he was from the press. One officer sustained a fractured skull. At least 400 people were arrested, including two journalists. [size=at least 400]

ACTOR2: Police Forces of the United States (2017-)
SOURCE: Physicians for Human Rights; New York Times; KUT90.5; AP; CBS Austin; Texas Tribune
NOTES: On 31 May 2020, people gathered in protest near the police headquarters in Austin (Texas) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. Police intervened to disperse the crowd with rubber bullets, pepper spray and bean bag rounds. Officers were stationed outside the headquarters and at the I-35 overpass, which caused demonstrators to be "caught in the crossfire." Six demonstrators were shot in the head with bean bag rounds by police. One of these demonstrators was a minor who sustained a severe skull fracture and damage to his prefrontal cortex. At least four of the demonstrators hit in the head with bean bag rounds required surgery for their injuries. After a demonstrator threw a water bottle and backpack at officers, police claimed they mistakenly shot a different demonstrator multiple times in the head and neck with beanbag rounds, sending him into critical condition at the hospital. Police fired on volunteer medics as they attempted to carry this demonstrator to safety, hitting at least one medic with a bean bag round. No evidence indicated that demonstrators shot in the head and neck "presented a threat of serious injury or death to officers or others." A photographer and a reporter were also hit while covering the protest. No arrests were reported. Seven police officers were placed on administrative leave in connection with five incidents of excessive force during the protest. [size=no report]

NOTES: On 31 May 2020, thousands of people participated in a demonstration in Minneapolis (Minnesota) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. The man scuffled with demonstrators and was then treated for minor injuries. The police took the driver into custody, charged with assault and was subsequently released. Later in the evening, the police arrested 276 demonstrators due to breach of curfew. National Guards were on the ground in the Twin Cities (Minneapolis and St. Paul) to support the police. NOTES: On 31 May 2020, hundreds of people gathered at Huizenga Park in Fort Lauderdale (Florida) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. Police tear gassed the demonstrators, who threw rocks and bottles in response. Some demonstrators threw concrete blocks at the windows of restaurants. A woman was severely injured after being shot in the head by a 40 mm foam-tipped round fired by a Fort Lauderdale police officer. Another man was shot in the lip at close range by a rubber bullet fired by police. The shot ripped a hole in his lip, broke a tooth, and fractured his jaw. On the same day, a large crowd gathered near the Broward County main library in Fort Lauderdale for the same cause. The police used tear gas to disperse the crowds after someone threw a water bottle at police. Demonstrators threw gas canisters back at police and damaged police vehicles. 2 people were arrested. [size=hundreds]

SOURCE: Crowd Counting Consortium; Indiana Daily Student
NOTES: On 1 June 2020, about 150 people marched in Bloomington (Indiana in support) of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. The protestors blocked roads. Later in the evening, a truck with American and Trump 2020 flags drove toward the crowd. Protesters surrounded the truck, screaming anti-Trump chants as the truck drove through the crowd. When the driver broke out of the group, he waved what appeared to be a handgun out his window. Some protesters tore the flags off the back of the truck and lit it on fire. [size=about 150]

NOTES: On 1 June 2020, nearly 400 people staged a protest in Lafayette (Iowa) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. Some police knelt with protesters after an invitation was extended. At night, police intervened and arrested a handful of people for disorderly conduct. ACTOR2: Police Forces of the United States (2017-)
NOTES: On 1 June 2020, an unreported number of people staged a demonstration in Wichita (Kansas) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd. At night, the demonstration turned violent when rioters damaged property, vandalized stores by breaking windows and threw cinder blocks, rocks, bottles and other objects at police. Police intervened with tear gas, smoke rounds, flash grenades and foam bullets. A demonstrator reportedly shot at an officer during the event. The individual was later arrested and charged. Two other people were arrested and three officers received minor injuries. [size=no report]

NOTES: On 5 June 2020, around 200 people marched in Overton Square to the Cooper-Young neighborhood in midtown Memphis (Tennessee) in support of Black Lives Matter movement and racial injustice in the wake of the death of George Floyd. The driver was charged with four counts of Reckless Endangerment and one count of Reckless Driving. In a separate incident at the same location, another driver drove through the crowd, though no one was struck or injured. The second driver was cited for disregarding a red light. ACTOR2: Sole Perpetrator (United States)
SOURCE: Pensacola News Journal; Palm Beach Post; Crowd Counting Consortium; Stamford Advocate
NOTES: On 6 June 2020, hundreds of people staged a protest in Pensacola (Florida) in support of the Black Lives Matter movement and against police brutality and the death of George Floyd.
